      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: ORLANDO, Fla., June 29 (AP) - Scientists suspect bacteria whose growth was encouraged by warm, wet weather and acid rain killed about 40 bald eagles before they could hatch, according to Steve Sherrod, director of an Oklahoma bird research center.</p>
        <p>ORLANDO, Fla., June 29 (AP) - Scientists suspect bacteria whose growth was encouraged by warm, wet weather and acid rain killed about 40 bald eagles before they could hatch, according to Steve Sherrod, director of an Oklahoma bird research center.</p>
        <p>The deaths were discovered earlier this year in a eagle study project here.</p>
        <p>At first, some scientists thought radioactivity might have enabled the bacteria to penetrate the eggs' shells. Others theorized that radioactivity had been the direct cause of death. Earlier, researchers had found that hatchings among 49 species of birds in California declined 65 percent after the explosion and fire at a reactor in the Soviet Union released radiation into the atmosphere.</p>
      </block>
